Downloading Data from Tidycensus

acs_vars <- c("B01001_001E", # ACS total Pop estimate
              "B25002_001E", # Estimate of total housing units
              "B25002_003E", # Number of vacant housing units
              "B19013_001E", # Median HH Income ($)
              "B02001_002E", # People describing themselves as "white alone"
              "B06009_006E") # Total graduate or professional degree

Call the Census API to get tract level data for 2020 for all of Philadelphia

acsTractsPHL.2020 <- get_acs(geography = "tract",
                             year = 2020, 
                             variables = acs_vars, 
                             geometry = FALSE, 
                             state = "PA", 
                             county = "Philadelphia", 
                             output = "wide")

Wrangling Data with dplyr

Mutating, selecting and renaming variables

acsTractsPHL.2020 <- acsTractsPHL.2020 %>%
  dplyr::select (GEOID, NAME, all_of(acs_vars))

acsTractsPHL.2020 <- acsTractsPHL.2020 %>%
  rename (total_pop.2020 = B01001_001E,
          total_HU.2020 = B25002_001E,
          total_vacant.2020 = B25002_003E,
          med_HH_Income.2020 = B19013_001E,
          total_White.2020 = B02001_002E,
          total_GradDeg.2020 = B06009_006E)

acsTractsPHL.2020 <- acsTractsPHL.2020 %>%
  mutate(vacancyPct.2020 = total_vacant.2020/total_HU.2020,
         pctWhite.2020   = total_White.2020/total_pop.2020)
acsTractsPHL.2016 <- get_acs(geography = "tract",
                             year = 2016, 
                             variables = acs_vars,
                             geometry = FALSE,
                             state = "PA", 
                             county = "Philadelphia",
                             output = "wide") %>%
  dplyr::select (GEOID, NAME, all_of(acs_vars)) %>% 
  rename (total_pop.2016 = B01001_001E,
          total_HU.2016 = B25002_001E,
          total_vacant.2016 = B25002_003E,
          med_HH_Income.2016 = B19013_001E,
          total_White.2016 = B02001_002E,
          total_GradDeg.2016 = B06009_006E) %>%
  mutate(vacancyPct.2016 = total_vacant.2016/total_HU.2016,
         pctWhite.2016 = total_White.2016/total_pop.2016)

Joining data

allACS <- left_join(acsTractsPHL.2016, acsTractsPHL.2020,
                    by= c("GEOID"))

Doing column math using mutate

allACS <- allACS %>%
  mutate(change_med_HH_Income = med_HH_Income.2020 - (med_HH_Income.2016 * 1.08), 
         change_Grad_Degree_Pct = (total_GradDeg.2020/total_pop.2020)-(total_GradDeg.2016/total_pop.2016))

Comparing geographies

allACS <- allACS %>%

Spatial Data and Tidycensus

Assignment

  1. a ggplot plot city-wide - number of vacant housing units per tract in 2020 as a function of vacant housing units in 2016, (change in raw housing units, so 2020-2016, using “B25002_003E”, # Number of vacant housing units”, which is part of the acs_vars vector). Use the ggplot “color” parameter in the geom_point aesthetics to visualize which are the Mt. Airy tracts. Annotate this plot with a single sentence describing what it shows (not as a plot title, but within the markdown).
ggplot(allACS) +
  geom_point(aes(x = total_vacant.2016, y = total_vacant.2020,
             color = mtAiry)) +
  labs(
    title = "2020 Vacant Housing units as a Function of 2016 Vacant Housing units",
    caption = "Data: US Census Bureau, ACS 5-year estimates",
    x = "Total Vacant Housing Units in 2016", 
    y = "Total Vacant Housing Units in 2020")

Plot Annotation: Though some regions saw drastic changes in total number of vacant housing units between 2016 and 2020, the number of vacant housing units mostly remained consistent in most regions of Philadelphia.

  1. A ggplot map symbolizing the number of vacant housing units in 2016 as a percentage of total housing units (e.g. “total_HU.2016”) on a per-tract basis. Outline the Mt. Airy neighborhood on the map. Annotate this map with a single sentence describing what it shows or implies about Mt Airy and Philadelphia.
# now create ggplot map
ggplot()+
  geom_sf(data = acsTractsPHL.2016.sf, aes(fill = vacancyPct.2016),
          color = "transparent")+
  geom_sf(data = acsTractsPHL.2016.sf %>%
            filter(mtAiry == "MT AIRY") %>%
            st_union(),
          color = "white",
          fill = "transparent")+
  labs(
    title = "Percentage of Vacant Housing Units in 2016",
    subtitle = "",
    caption = "Data: US Census Bureau, ACS 5-year estimates",
    fill = "% Vacant Units")

Plot Annotation: About 20% of the total housing units in the Mt. Airy region are vacant, which can be said about the general Philadelphia area, but there is a higher percentage (closer to 40%) of vacant housing units in the upper West and North Philadelphia regions.

  1. Create a code chunk that renders a “kable” table showing a summary of mean number of vacant housing units per tract for Mt. Airy vs. the rest Philadelphia as a whole in 2020. Annotate this plot with a single sentence describing what it shows or implies about the data.
# make desired table
allACS %>%
  group_by(mtAiry) %>%
  summarize(mean_VacantUnits = mean(total_vacant.2020, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  kbl(caption = "Mean Vacant Units per tract in Mt. Airy vs Rest of Philadelphia",
      col.names = c("Region", "Mean number of Vacant Units")) %>%
  kable_classic(full_width = F, html_font = "Cambria")
Mean Vacant Units per tract in Mt. Airy vs Rest of Philadelphia
Region Mean number of Vacant Units
MT AIRY 156.625
REST OF PHILADELPHIA 196.893

Table Annotation: This Table shows us that the mean number of vacant units in Mt. Airy is lower compared to that of the rest of Philadelphia.
